     <article id="comment-32" data-id="981" itemprop="comment" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/UserComments">
      <header>
       <div class="avatar"><img src="https://gravatar.com/avatar/33bfe9dcefdf4998d865d5dcfb369365?s=30" alt="" width="30" height="30" srcset="https://gravatar.com/avatar/33bfe9dcefdf4998d865d5dcfb369365?s=60 2x"></div>
       <p class="meta"><span itemprop="creator" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><span itemprop="name">mahboud</span></span> wrote on <time datetime="2014-06-16T12:00" itemprop="commentTime"><a href="#comment-32" rel="bookmark" itemprop="url" title="Permanent link to comment 32 on “How to create simple Mac apps from shell scripts”">16th June 2014 at 12:00</a></time>:</p>
      </header>
      <div itemprop="commentText">
       <p>Use Automator to turn a shell script into an app. That way, the app can also act as a droplet: drag files onto it and the files will appear to the script as arguments, and are accessible via <code>$1</code>, <code>$2</code>, <code>$3</code> (or loop through them with <code>for f in "$@"</code>).</p>
       <p>Don’t waste your time with Appify or Platypus — they are either obsolete, bad-tempered or just not as intuitive and powerful as Automator.</p>
      </div>
     </article>
     <article id="comment-33" data-id="1036" itemprop="comment" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/UserComments">
      <header>
       <div class="avatar"><img src="https://gravatar.com/avatar/b9f5f08993eae8cc23c6e54b188428f1?s=30" alt="" width="30" height="30" srcset="https://gravatar.com/avatar/b9f5f08993eae8cc23c6e54b188428f1?s=60 2x"></div>
       <p class="meta"><span itemprop="creator" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><span itemprop="name">Jason</span></span> wrote on <time datetime="2014-09-10T23:22" itemprop="commentTime"><a href="#comment-33" rel="bookmark" itemprop="url" title="Permanent link to comment 33 on “How to create simple Mac apps from shell scripts”">10th September 2014 at 23:22</a></time>:</p>
      </header>
      <div itemprop="commentText">
       <p><a href="#comment-20"><strong>Don:</strong></a> It might be because you’re only subbing in one file size that is accepted, and a part of the <code>icns</code> package. To create a proper <code>icns</code> file, you can use the <code>iconutl - c icns &lt;iconset package&gt;</code> command, where the <code>&lt;iconset package&gt;</code> is the path to the folder holding the different accepted dimensions of the icon. You can also build in Xcode and have it auto-created. Not sure that’s the problem here, but off the top of my head it’s worth a look.</p>
      </div>
     </article>
